<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-12-12T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-12-12T06:00:00-05:00" n="624" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d624">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3179: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Forbes</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-12-12T20:00:00+09:00">December 12, 1931—8
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 12—11:40
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>259. Your telegram No. 262, December 11, 9 p.m.<note n="83" xml:id="d624fn83"><ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_62"><hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol.
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 62</ref>.</note> In view of
                            the resignation of the Cabinet, I shall await appointment of new Foreign
                            Minister before taking any action unless otherwise instructed. I have
                            just been informed that Inukai, President of the Seiyukai, has been
                            summoned to the Imperial Palace at 8 o’clock tonight. Unquestionably he
                            will be asked to form a new cabinet. As yet there are no reliable
                            indications of its composition.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Forbes</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
